	<article id="post-950" class="post-950 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-avr category-circuits category-electronics-guides category-microcontrollers category-msp430 category-pic tag-arduino tag-avr tag-calculation tag-ntc tag-pic tag-read tag-sensor tag-temperature tag-thermistor tag-tutorial tag-voltage-divider">
				<header class="entry-header">
			
						<h1 class="entry-title">
				<a href="http://eliaselectronics.com/measuring-temperature-with-your-microcontroller-using-ntcs/" rel="bookmark">Measuring temperature with your microcontroller using NTCs</a>
			</h1>
										<div class="comments-link">
					<a href="http://eliaselectronics.com/measuring-temperature-with-your-microcontroller-using-ntcs/#comments" title="Comment on Measuring temperature with your microcontroller using NTCs">4 Replies</a>				</div><!-- .comments-link -->
					</header><!-- .entry-header -->

				<div class="entry-content">
			<p>Often you want to measure environmental variables with your microcontroller, e.g. brightness, temperature, humidity, gas concentration etc.</p>
<p>Measuring a temperature with a microcontroller can be done in several different ways depending on the accuracy required and temperature range involved. A thermistor (temperature dependent resistor) can be used as a cheap temperature sensor for temperatures ranging from -40Â°C up to 125Â°C.<br />
 <a href="http://eliaselectronics.com/measuring-temperature-with-your-microcontroller-using-ntcs/#more-950" class="more-link">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&rarr;</span></a></p>
					</div><!-- .entry-content -->
		
